AudioData.Text: This is the Cleanup Tool, also known as the Spoon Excavator. Its spoon-shaped tip is perfect for gently scooping out soft, decayed material from cavities. You’ll use this to clean out the damaged tissue and ensure the tooth is ready for restoration, like a filling or crown. Be precise and gentle—your patients depend on it

Meet the Measuring Stick, or the Williams Probe. Those small markings along its length? They measure the depth of gum pockets, giving you critical information about your patient’s periodontal health. Use it to determine if gum disease has progressed and to plan treatments that maintain strong, healthy gums.

Say hello to the Decay Detector, or Dental Explorer. Its fine, sharp tip is excellent for identifying cavities, rough spots, and imperfections on the tooth surface. Gently run it along the enamel to locate sticky or soft areas—early signs of decay that need treatment. This tool is your key to catching problems before they worsen.

Your Reflection Assistant is indispensable. Use it to see areas of the mouth that would otherwise stay hidden—behind teeth, under arches, and into those hard-to-reach corners. It’s also great for redirecting light to illuminate dark areas, making your examinations more thorough and accurate.

Here we have the Plaque Remover, also known as the Curette or Scaler. This tool scrapes away tartar and plaque from tooth surfaces and beneath the gumline. It’s a must for deep cleaning treatments and helps keep gums healthy by preventing infections and decay. Precision is key, especially when working near the gumline.

The Polisher is next. This low-speed handpiece operates at a slower pace than its high-speed counterpart, making it ideal for smoothing restorations, adjusting prosthetics, and polishing teeth during cleanings. The result? Teeth that are smooth, shiny, and ready for a bright smile.

This is the Swift Cutter, or Air Turbine Handpiece. Lightweight and incredibly fast, it’s your go-to for cavity preparation and crown adjustments. Its precision is unmatched, making it ideal for delicate, intricate procedures that require a steady hand and a sharp focus.

Time to meet the Precision Shaper, also known as the Dental Drill. It spins at incredibly high speeds to quickly remove decayed material and smoothen tooth surfaces. You’ll rely on it for shaping cavities and prepping teeth for fillings or crowns. Its speed and accuracy make it a cornerstone of restorative work.

Finally, the Power Cleaner, or Ultrasonic Scaler. This tool uses high-frequency vibrations to break apart hardened plaque and tartar that brushing can’t remove. It’s perfect for cleaning both above and below the gumline, leaving teeth polished and healthy. A game-changer for deep cleaning sessions!

Congratulations, You have Completed the tutorial. You’ve been introduced to your essential tools. Each one has a unique purpose, and together, they’re your arsenal for effective and precise dental care.

Welcome to the Dental Lab! In this session, you'll be introduced to various dental tools. I'll walk you through each one, explaining what they are and how they're used. Take your time to observe and familiarize yourself—no need to test them yet!
